<div><a name="page-1"></a></div>
<p>"Verified" accounts on Elon Musk's X platform spread nearly three-quarters of the 250 most viral posts containing commonly shared misinformation about the Israel-Hamas war, according to a <a href="https://www.newsguardtech.com/misinformation-monitor/october-2023/">study released yesterday</a> by NewsGuard, a company that has worked with the European Commission on misinformation initiatives.</p>
<p>After buying Twitter nearly a year ago, Musk overhauled the system for doling out blue checkmarks so that anyone who <a href="https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2023/03/twitter-to-un-verify-people-who-dont-pay-8-month-starting-on-april-fools-day/">pays $8 a month</a> can be "verified." Accounts verified as being notable and authentic under the pre-Musk system had their checkmarks removed.</p>
<p>"A NewsGuard analysis found that 'verified' accounts on X are superspreaders of misinformation about the conflict, boosting falsehoods while displaying a 'verification' blue checkmark that verifies nothing," the report said.</p></div><p><a href="https://arstechnica.com/?p=1977478#p3">Read 20 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href="https://arstechnica.com/?p=1977478&comments=1">Comments</a></p>